AWS detected a new form of ransomware attack, where attackers use SSE-C to overwrite your S3 data and re-encrypt them with the attacker's key.

Presumably, you'd have to pay them a ransom in exchange for the key to regain access to your data.

So now, they recommend disabling the use of SSE-C unless you need it. And, to enable S3 versioning to support data recovery in case they are deleted and overwritten.

Read more in this blog post:

https://t.co/KvhEbIekko

result.text:
Forget Japan visa, enter Korean visa. 
This is next level profiling. 

Applied yesterday, no interview. The whole center was empty,  probably because Korea is famous for notorious refusals.  

Fees is 4580 INR card accepted 

Documents required are exactly as per checklist. 

No cover letter accepted,  no air tickets needed neither any hotel reservations, no photo required. 

Fill visa application form from here:- https://t.co/XxITl1V49Q once done a pdf will be created. 

Now VFS will sort and arrange documents as per checklist and on top they will memtion with pen all the  big countries visa you hold in mine he wrote usa, uk, Schengen, Canada and Japan. 

Fun starts the next day, I got an email seems to be an automated one, where they have outsourced the docs verification to a third party company seems to be uae based to take my pan card number and login password of income tax website and all the bank statements which were submitted at the time of application to be uploaded again in their portal and pay another 10 USD ü•≤üòÄ

Well, that's a humbling process. Koreans must love us. I didn't feel very comfortable but what can I even do. 

And hey not to forget, they have put many notices in the visa application about how embassy has uncovered visa fraud done by Indians, they have also put forward a notice of FIR made against few applications. Why were these Indian's trying to illegaly go to Korea? And do exactly what there?

result.text:
Build a knowledge graph agent from scratch üî•

I'm super excited about this blog post by Tomaz Bratanic from @neo4j - this is probably the most thorough treatment I've seen for building a text-to-cypher powered knowledge graph agent that actually works well. 

Tomaz walks through an entire list of potential strategies and evaluates them according to a standardized benchmark: 

1. Naive text-to-cypher
2. Text-to-cypher with retry and evaluation
3. Iterative planning system by generating a plan of sub-queries before creating the final query.

All of these can be stitched together as an event-driven system with @llama_index workflows. 

Check out the post! https://t.co/n86ikA0Uti

If you want to get your hands dirty on workflows check out our guide here: https://t.co/tNolgSm48v
